WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:00.993
And so on.

00:01.834 --> 00:04.920
So the question, of course, is how do you train this model?

00:05.080 --> 00:08.867
How do you train a model that gives you good candidates for subdivision?

00:09.508 --> 00:15.880
And the answer here comes from the idea of hindsight experience replay.

00:15.860 --> 00:19.764
So let's say, again, you are here and you want to go here.

00:20.304 --> 00:24.468
And you're not very good at it initially.

00:25.069 --> 00:30.655
So they train this model, as I understand, along with letting their agent act in this environment.

00:31.075 --> 00:34.458
So the agent uses the model to plan, but initially it's not very good.

00:34.719 --> 00:37.321
So maybe the agent will fail a lot of times.

00:37.681 --> 00:44.348
So instead of going to the blue square, it will reach this white square right here.

00:44.328 --> 00:53.851
It will go here here and here who reached the white square instead of saying I failed what you can do and this is the idea of hindsight experience replay is.

00:54.513 --> 01:00.868
To say well I did fail but I did reach something right I have reached a thing.

01:00.848 --> 01:08.155
And it's actually possible that that thing could have been the goal, but this particular episode, this was the goal.

01:08.315 --> 01:09.917
Remember, the goal changes every time.

01:09.957 --> 01:12.679
It's a goal directed policy.

01:12.940 --> 01:15.762
So it says, well, this could have been the goal, possibly.

01:16.043 --> 01:23.550
So if I just pretend this was the goal, then I have a training example for a successful run.

01:24.010 --> 01:28.054
So the hindsight experience replay basically pretends that what you

01:28.034 --> 01:31.497
have achieved, even if you failed, was your actual goal.

01:31.998 --> 01:36.082
And that gives you a positive training example for an episode with that as a goal.

01:36.623 --> 01:42.088
And it could have been the goal because the goal is chosen at random.

01:43.229 --> 01:45.752
So this gives you a good training example.

01:46.232 --> 01:52.278
Now this paper just generalizes the hindsight experience replay or applies it to their particular framework.

01:52.598 --> 01:56.202
And they say, well, if I reach this thing, that means

01:56.182 --> 02:05.353
Any point on this path is a good candidate for subdividing the path, because I did actually reach the point.

02:05.594 --> 02:12.983
Remember, the goal is to propose a point where your foreshore are going to pass through.

02:13.023 --> 02:21.594
Now, since I've taken this path to this goal, I have passed through any of the squares in between, and so these are my possible sub-candidates.

02:21.754 --> 02:25.058
And all other black squares, I don't want that.

02:25.038 --> 02:33.430
So now I have a classifier I can train, I can say any of these squares on my path are good squares to subdivide and any not on my path are bad ones.

02:33.890 --> 02:45.847
They go a step further, I believe, and they actually say we're, so if this was m steps, we're actually going to take the particular square that is reached after m half steps.

02:45.907 --> 02:51.315
So the exact middle point of that path is going to be our,

02:51.295 --> 02:54.901
training example for subdivisions.

02:54.961 --> 03:02.052
So you have a classifier that has exactly one target to train.

03:02.072 --> 03:05.858
So this you train along with acting in the environment.

03:05.978 --> 03:11.667
And of course, your model for proposing subdivisions is going to be better and better and better and better.

03:11.647 --> 03:16.071
And that makes your planning algorithm better and better, and that makes you collect better episodes.

03:16.471 --> 03:24.558
And so you can sort of bootstrap yourself up this thing.

03:25.719 --> 03:29.482
Now, this is the basic experiment of the paper.

03:29.543 --> 03:35.187
They also do this in a 3D manner, where they move this little spider here around.

03:35.227 --> 03:41.653
So the spider was trained to just move from one block to the next block, and the planner basically has to tell it where to go.

03:41.633 --> 03:48.007
And they show that they outperformed the traditional Monte Carlo tree search.

03:48.027 --> 03:58.470
Now, I have to say this is cool, but you have to remember this is only advantageous in very, very specific types of problems.

03:58.490 --> 04:01.296
So first of all, it has to be this goal-directed nature.

04:01.276 --> 04:07.488
Otherwise, you probably couldn't train this predictor here super well.

04:07.949 --> 04:14.222
Then, given that you have such a good predictor, the problem needs to be such that

04:16.126 --> 04:21.619
If you have a start state, there could be many ways to go about reaching the end.

04:22.000 --> 04:25.608
And if you have an end state, there could be many ways from where you could come from.

04:26.110 --> 04:34.810
But there is some bottleneck state in the middle where you're pretty sure that you're going to have to pass through it.

04:34.790 --> 04:50.487
If your problem is of that nature, if it has these bottleneck states where you can predict with reasonable accuracy that you're going to have to pass through, then this is a good algorithm to consider.

04:50.467 --> 05:06.452
is intuitively outperforming the original Monte Carlo tree search because you have much less deep search tree and you can effectively limit its width by using that model.

05:07.253 --> 05:14.044
They also have made this website where they show videos of their spider and

05:14.024 --> 05:18.088
I haven't seen it in a while, but it is, it is like next to the mouse.

05:18.508 --> 05:19.249
If you can see it.

05:19.709 --> 05:25.955
So, so you, you see, this is kind of a continuous control problem that also requires planning.

05:26.475 --> 05:31.680
And they also have these kind of gifts of how they're, they're, what order their plans are constructed in.

05:32.541 --> 05:34.763
So I invite you to check this out, read the paper.

05:35.303 --> 05:41.228
Uh, if you like this, uh, subscribe, leave a like, leave a comment, and thank you for listening.

05:41.589 --> 05:41.989
Bye-bye.

